    {
      "name":"ClickjackingVulnerability",
      "id":"ClickjackingVulnerability",
      "description":"Clickjacking (also known as a UI redress attack) is when an attacker uses multiple transparent or opaque layers to trick a user into clicking on a button or link on another page when they were intending to click on the top-level page. Clickjacking attacks exploit the ability of browsers to embed pages in iframes. An attacker creates a malicious page that loads the target site in a transparent iframe overlaid on top of a decoy UI. When the user clicks what they think is a legitimate button, they are actually clicking on the hidden, embedded page. \u003Cbr/\u003E\u003Cbr/\u003EThe primary defenses against clickjacking are HTTP response headers that instruct the browser whether a page is allowed to be framed. \u003Cbr/\u003E\u003Cbr/\u003EImportant Links:\u003Cbr/\u003E\u003Col\u003E \u003Cli\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Clickjacking\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EOWASP Clickjacking Attack\u003C/a\u003E  \u003Cli\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Clickjacking_Defense_Cheat_Sheet.html\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EOWASP Clickjacking Defense Cheat Sheet\u003C/a\u003E \u003Cli\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1021.html\" target=\"_blank\"\u003ECWE-1021: Improper Restriction of Rendered UI Layers or Frames\u003C/a\u003E \u003Cli\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/X-Frame-Options\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EMDN: X-Frame-Options\u003C/a\u003E \u003Cli\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Content-Security-Policy/frame-ancestors\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EMDN: CSP frame-ancestors\u003C/a\u003E \u003C/ol\u003E",
      "vulnerabilityTypes":[
         
      ],
